{"cursor":"3117","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{Interventions infobox | Name = Salvage therapy | Image = | Caption = | ICD10 =\n| ICD9unlinked = | MeshID = D016879 | OPS301 = | OtherCodes = | }} 'Salvage\ntherapy', also known as 'rescue therapy', is a form of treatment given after an\nailment does not respond to standard treatment. {{cite web\n  | last = first = authorlink = coauthors = title = Definition of Salvage\n  | therapy work = publisher = MedicineNet.com year = 2006 url =\n  | http://www.medterms.com/script/main/art.asp?articlekey=9380 format = doi =\n  | accessdate = 2006-10-26 }}\n The most common diseases that require salvage therapy are HIV and various\ntumors. The word is not clearly defined; it is used both to mean a second\nattempt and a final attempt. {{cite web\n  | last = first = authorlink = coauthors = title = HIV Therapy 2006 work =\n  | publisher = Flying Publisher year = 2006 url =\n  | http://www.hivmedicine.com/textbook/haart/salvage.htm doi = accessdate =\n  | 2006-10-26 }}\n Salvage therapy drugs or drug combinations have, in general, much more\nsevere side effects than the standard line of therapy.\n","linknr":113,"url":"Salvage_therapy","recorded":1363416774,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Salvage_therapy&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Salvage_therapy&action=edit","//en.wikipedia.org/apple-touch-icon.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.wikihiero%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/l